"1226–1303":"1226–1303","1226–1307":"1226–1307","1234–1309":"1234–1309","1240–1287":"1240–1287","1245–1293":"1245–1293","1252–Female":"1252–Overleden","1254–Female":"1254–Overleden","1180–Male":"1180–Overleden","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1293":"1293","1180":"1180","4 September 1287":"4 september 1287","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","1226":"1226","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","1254":"1254","1287":"1287","about 1200":"circa 1200","1309":"1309","1307":"1307","Walsall, Staffordshire, England":"Walsall, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bicester, Oxfordshire, England":"Bicester, Oxfordshire, England"},"en":{"about 1200–4 September 1287":"about 1200–4 September 1287","1200–1287":"1200–1287","1226–1303":"1226–1303","1226–1307":"1226–1307","1234–1309":"1234–1309","1240–1287":"1240–1287","1245–1293":"1245–1293","1252–Female":"1252–Deceased","1254–Female":"1254–Deceased","1180–Male":"1180–Deceased","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1293":"1293","1180":"1180","4 September 1287":"4 September 1287","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","1226":"1226","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","1254":"1254","1287":"1287","about 1200":"about 1200","1309":"1309","1307":"1307","Walsall, Staffordshire, England":"Walsall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Bicester, Oxfordshire, England":"Bicester, Oxfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"la","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Cuong, Anh, Thanh, Ha, Hoang, Tuan, Chau, Hao, Hien, Hoa, Hue, Nam, Phong, Sinh, Tuong, Min, Tam, Tanh, Thai, Tham, Tinh, Yeong.  Chinese Hong, Hang, Sang, Tong, Chan, Chi, Hwa Ja, Hyung, Kam, Ki Bong, Kin, Man.","Vietnamese: from the Chinese surname 羅, see   Luo   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Lã</b>): from the Chinese surname 呂, see   Lu   6 and 3 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Luo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Jian, Yi, Ping, Yong, Zhen, Feng, Hong, Ming, Jin, Bin, Chen, Hai, Lan, Min, Huan, Hung, Shen, Tian.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 羅, meaning ‘net for catching birds’ or ‘to collect’ in Chinese: (i) from Luo (羅), the name of an ancient state (located in present-day Hubei province). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the early Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), people from the state migrated southwards and adopted Luo (羅) as their surname. (ii) from the Po Duo Luo (破多羅) and Chi Luo (叱羅) families from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China, who changed their original surnames to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) from the personal name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅), leader of an ancient Turkic tribe who are believed to have migrated to China during the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ). His descendants inherited his name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅) as their surname and shortened it to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) from the name of one of the seven families from the Bandun Man, an ethnic group residing in ancient southwestern China (located mainly in present-day Sichuan province)."]}]},{"name":"Wade","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Wade</i> (Old English <i>Wada</i> or, via Norman French, from ancient Germanic <i>Wado</i>, of unclear origin but possibly related to Old English <i>wadan</i> ‘to go’).","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>wade</i> ‘ford’ (Old English <i>(ge)wæd</i> ‘ford, especially a tidal crossing’) for someone who lived by a ford, or a habitational name from a place so called, such as Wade Hall in North Cove (Suffolk).","Irish: shortened and altered from <b>Mac Uaid</b>, see   McQuaid  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wadeson","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Wade  ."]},{"name":"Wass","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Wace</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Waz(z)o</i>), a pet form of any of various ancient Germanic personal names beginning with <i>Wad-</i> (compare   Wade   1). The name <i>Wace</i> was common among the Normans, alongside the Parisian French variant <i>Gace</i>, and was latinized as <i>Wazo</i> (nominative), <i>Wazonis</i> (genitive).","English (of Norman origin): occasionally, perhaps a variant of   Vause   with vocalizing of initial <i>V-</i>.","German: nickname from Middle High German <i>was(se)</i> ‘sharp, cutting’."]},{"name":"Waide","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Wade  .","German: variant of   Weide  .","Irish: shortened form of <b>Mac Uaid</b>, see   McQuaid  ."]},{"name":"Waddy","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Wadey</b>, perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Wady</i>, a pet form of   Wade  , or in northern England alternatively a shortened form of   Waldo  . The name may also be a variant of   Wilday  ."]},{"name":"McQuaid","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Colum, Nuala.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Uaid</b> ‘son of <i>Uad</i>’, Gaelic form of the personal name <i>Wat</i>, a short form of   Walter  . Compare the Scottish form   McQuate  ."]},{"name":"Waithe","meanings":["English:","either a topographic name from Old Norse <i>vath</i> ‘ford’, or a habitational name from a place so named, such as Waithe (Lincolnshire) and Wath (North and Yorkshire).","variant of   Wade  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":15,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":24,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":59,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdicti